For the solving of a linear system A x = b, there are 2 possibilities:

1: The CHOLESKY FACTORIZATION A = L Lt, with a SKYLINE storage.
   If the matrix is inversible, the solution is always obtained.
   But, this method uses a big memory, notably in 3D.

2: The PRECONDITIONED CONJUGATE GRADIENT with a SPARSE storage
   occupies less memories than the skyline storage, but, this method
   may not converge in some cases (in Elasticity for example).
                                                
   If this option 2 is chosen, the value of LEVEL is requested
   It characterizes the storage of the incomplete Cholesky factorization
   used for the preconditionement:

   - LEVEL=0 The matrix of preconditionement has the same storage than A.

   - LEVEL>0 The matrix of preconditionement has a growing storage
     which leads to have a matrix nearer of the complete Cholesky matrix
     and the preconditionement is better.
